<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-877-720  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 877 720.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Classroom Computer Learning  Oct 1989 v10 n2 p30(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>National Geographic Kids Network: real science in the elementaryclassroom. (on-line information exchange for grades 4-6; includesrelated articles on how to sign up for Kids Network and availablefunding for similar secondary school science programs)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Julyan, Candace L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>National Geographic (NG) Kids Network allows students to collectand analyze data, then share findings with others on thetelecommunications network.andP;  The curriculum was developed by theTechnical Education Research Centers with funding from theNational Science Foundation.andP;  The introductory unit asks studentsto collect data about pets.andP;  They compare with classmates, thenreport findings to pre-assigned student teams doing similarresearch in 10 locations around the country.andP;  Information is alsorecorded on a computer form; the NG staff publishes anddistributes a report to participants within a week.andP;  Students thencan follow up on discrepancies or points of interest in others'research, as do adult scientists involved in original research.andO;Teachers in the field test report high interest level among allstudents.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CurriculumScienceNetworksEducationNational Geographic Society.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>